article.headline: Washington 72, Washington State 54
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- When the Washington Huskies started the second
half in a sleepy daze, coach June Daugherty shook them awake.

Giuliana Mendiola had 18 points and six assists while Andrea
Lalum added 15 points and six rebounds as Washington won its 17th
straight over Washington State, beating the Cougars 72-54 on
Saturday.

Washington's two senior leaders led a decisive burst after the
Cougars (4-14, 0-9 Pac-10) scored the first seven points of the
second half. Lalum scored twice to ignite a key 15-4 run, and
Mendiola had six points in the stretch.

"We had a little shaky start coming out of the gate in the
second half," Daugherty said. "When we settled down, we looked
pretty good. We shared the basketball and we were getting it done
as a team."

The Huskies (11-7, 4-5 Pac-10) got solid performances from
freshmen Cheri Craddock, who scored 11 points, and Cameo Hicks, who
had 10.

"Our team's confidence has gone up," Mendiola said. "We were
a little down after some early Pac-10 losses but we didn't lose our
confidence."

Kate Benz led Washington State with 15 points and 10 rebounds
while Stephanie Singer added 10 points.

Washington State, which has only one Pac-10 victory in the last
three seasons, hasn't beaten Washington since 1996. The Cougars
haven't won in Seattle since a 75-72 overtime victory in 1993.

This one was a game of swings, with the Cougars building an
early 16-14 lead. The Huskies answered when Craddock scored on a
jumper and a layup and Breanne Watson added a three-point play
during a 14-0 burst.

"We did a good job taking them out of their sets, and they'd
just go one-on-one," Cougars coach Sherri Murrell said. "They
broke us down, not because of their offense, but because of what
their individuals did."

Washington State never went away, despite going scoreless for a
stretch of almost five minutes in each half.

"Do we really look like we're 0-9?" Murrell asked. "No, but
you have to step up and you have to sustain it individually."

The Cougars trimmed the deficit to 37-33 late in the first half
and trailed 41-33 at the break. Washington State scored the first
seven points of the second half -- a jumper by Benz, a 3-pointer
from Singer and a layup by Candace Fields -- to trim the margin to
41-40.

"We were just in slow motion," Daugherty said. "We were
caught standing defensively. We were giving up way too much, too
easy."

Daugherty called a timeout, and Washington turned to Lalum and
Mendiola. Lalum scored twice and Mendiola had six points during the
decisive run that put the Huskies back in control.

"We were pretty proud we were able to make them take a timeout
after a 7-0 run," Murrell said. "The difference is this team is
used to losing. I told them, 'You have to go out there expecting to
keep running at them."

Craddock hit a 3-pointer during that run and another freshman,
Maggie O'Hara, scored a fastbreak layup to cap Washington's burst.

"The things we talked about at halftime weren't happening and
you expect them to happen coming out of the gate," Daugherty said.
"We needed some reminders, a quick wakeup call and they
responded."
